Shared-Link Perturbation and Geometric Delay: A Graph-Theoretic Derivation of the Optical Refractive Index Spectrum Based on a TDMU Toy Model

Abstract
The Topological Discrete Membrane Universe (TDMU) framework interprets light as coupled transverse waves of shared-link density and orientation-degree waves on a topological membrane. Under this framework, the slowing of light in a medium originates from the additional reconnection steps (geometric delay) imposed on an incident perturbation by atomic topological knots. This paper constructs a toy model: atoms of a medium are modeled as regular graphs with discrete dangling ports. Starting from the underlying discrete reconnection rules, a continuous wave equation is derived in the long-wavelength limit. Spectral graph theory is employed to compute the frequency response function 
