7. Discussion
The result of this paper constitutes a specific type of “existence proof”: the dispersion behavior of medium optics—whose functional form is a universal feature of linear resonant systems, but whose parameters are entirely numerical—can emerge naturally from fully discrete graph dynamics in the long-wavelength limit, without recourse to electromagnetic constitutive relations or the wave function assumption of quantum mechanics. In other words, this paper proves that the phenomenological parameters of medium optics, rather than their formula form, have a purely geometric origin.

Any competitive underlying unified theory must first fully recover all known results of mature older theories in the low-energy limit. The TDMU optical framework passes this test: without relying on the concept of electromagnetic fields, and without introducing phenomenological oscillator parameters, relying solely on discrete topological reconnection rules and spectral graph theory, it obtains in the long-wavelength approximation a dispersion function that is mathematically isomorphic to the Lorentz oscillator model.

The mathematical results of this paper do not depend on the ontological commitments of the TDMU framework. Even if the reader does not accept the premise that “the universe is woven from a topological membrane and fundamental bricks,” the graph-theoretic dynamical derivation presented in this paper is mathematically self-consistent: it demonstrates that there exists a class of graph structures whose frequency response to an external drive naturally exhibits classical dispersion behavior. Therefore, this paper at least constitutes a contribution in a weaker sense: it provides a new mathematical description language for the dispersion phenomena of medium optics, whose parameters possess clear geometric/combinatorial interpretations. The value of the TDMU framework lies in providing a physical ontology for this mathematical structure—the graph is not an artificially chosen fitting tool, but the real mode of existence of matter on the underlying topological membrane. Unlike existing topological photonics [8] and graph-theoretic models of dielectric response [9]—the former studying macroscopic artificial structures, the latter using graphs as an effective discretization approximation of the medium—in this paper, the graph is the underlying ontology of the medium. This is the essential dividing line between the TDMU optical framework and all existing theories of dispersion.

Subsequent work will advance along the following paths: (1) lift the long-wavelength approximation by running discrete reconnection simulations directly on the toy graph; (2) substitute cores of different symmetries and compute the regularity of resonance peak ratios; (3) construct multi-atom coupled graphs and explore collective modes; (4) carry out the air-anchored calibration to obtain the first numerical estimate of 
