In the weak-coupling limit, the model produces a frequency response function that is mathematically equivalent in structure to the classical Lorentz oscillator—this equivalence is a universal feature of linear resonant systems and is not an original contribution of this paper. The unique contribution of this paper is that the realization of this equivalence does not rely at all on electromagnetic fields, dielectric constants, or wave functions, and all core parameters are uniquely determined by the features of the graph Laplacian spectrum. This paper provides an alternative mathematical framework, using the language of graph theory, to completely describe medium dispersion, with parameters possessing clear geometric/combinatorial interpretations. The three differentiating predictions to which the framework naturally points—high-frequency discrete cutoff, rational ratio constraints on resonance peaks, and direct association between polarization and port topology—provide clear, actionable, and falsifiable verification pathways for the TDMU optical framework.

This paper presents a complete, reproducible, and improvable computational paradigm. The physical approximations, artificial construction choices, and undetermined parameters at the current stage have all been listed in full, stratified by category. The numerical verification pathways for each step of improvement are explicitly given in Section 5, and the calibration protocol for the global scale parameter is established in Section 4.2. The further maturation of the framework will proceed along these pathways to progressively remove the current limitations.

